description:
### What happens?

Hi, duckdb team.

It seems duckdb use GOO algorithm to handle approximate join reorder and add cross product if there is no connection between relations. It is supposed to select two tables with the lowest cost when adding a connection, however it seems this piece of code doesn't look as expected. 
```
// if there are any other join relations that don't have connections
// add them if they have lower estimated cardinality.
for (idx_t i = 2; i < join_relations.size(); i++) {
  // get the plan for this relation
  optional_ptr<DPJoinNode> current_plan = plans[join_relations[i]];
  // check if the cardinality is smaller than the smallest two found so far
  for (idx_t j = 0; j < 2; j++) {
    if (!smallest_plans[j] || smallest_plans[j]->cost > current_plan->cost) {
      smallest_plans[j] = current_plan;
      smallest_index[j] = i;
      break;
    }
  }
}
```
If we have tables with **decreasing** rows(aka decreasing cardinality/cost) as follow:
NOTE: I change THRESHOLD_TO_SWAP_TO_APPROXIMATE to 8 for the convenience of the test.
```
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table1(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table1 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5),(3, 1, 1, 3, 4),(4, 2, 2, 4, 3), (5, 2, 1, 5, 2),(6, 2, 2, 6, null),(7, 1, 1, 1, 6),(8, 1, 2, 2, 5)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table2(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table2 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5),(3, 1, 1, 3, 4),(4, 2, 2, 4, 3), (5, 2, 1, 5, 2),(6, 2, 2, 6, null), (7, 1, 1, 1, 6)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table3(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table3 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5),(3, 1, 1, 3, 4),(4, 2, 2, 4, 3), (5, 2, 1, 5, 2),(6, 2, 2, 6, null)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table4(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table4 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5),(3, 1, 1, 3, 4),(4, 2, 2, 4, 3), (5, 2, 1, 5, 2)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table5(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table5 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5),(3, 1, 1, 3, 4),(4, 2, 2, 4, 3)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table6(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table6 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5),(3, 1, 1, 3, 4)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table7(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table7 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6),(2, 1, 2, 2, 5)");
con.Query("CREATE TABLE table8(key0 INTEGER primary key, col0 INTEGER, col1 INTEGER, col2 INTEGER, col3 INTEGER)");
con.Query("INSERT INTO table8 VALUES (1, 1, 1, 1, 6)");
```

It generate suboptimal plan like this:

join_relations: all table with cost as 0 at the beginning
t1 = t2 = t3 = t4 = t5 = t6 = t7 = t8

join_relations:
t12 > t34 > t56 > t78
smallest_plans: [t12, t34] --> [t56, t34]  --> [t78, t34] --> t3478. Not **[t56, t78]** we expected

join_relations:
t12 > t56 > t3478
smallest_plans: [t12, t56] --> t1256

join_relations:
t1256, t3478

